6Ô∏è‚É£ Avoid redundant operations: Make sure your SQL queries are optimised to avoid redundant operations that are not needed. For example, if you are filtering data with a WHERE clause, make sure you are not filtering the same data in a subsequent JOIN operation.
4Ô∏è‚É£ Use WHERE clauses to filter data: Do this as soon as you can. You can use WHERE clauses to increase the efficiency of your queries and filter the data you want to retrieve.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Use descriptive table and column names: It's important to use descriptive names for tables and columns, by doint it you can improve the readability and comprehension of your queries for other people who may be working with your code.

1Ô∏è‚É£ Understand the data you're dealing with: It's crucial to have a firm grasp of the data you're working with before writing SQL queries. This includes the structure of the database, the relationships between tables, and the types of data stored in each column.

For those who aren't familar with it, in streaming mode Polars processes your query in batches rather than all-at-once.

Streaming allows you to scale to much larger than memory data on your laptop.

And all you need to do is end your lazy query with `.collect(streaming=True)`

So don't think of streaming as some kind or emergency switch you invoke when you've tried everything else to get your query to fit in memory.

It may actually be a solid default in many cases - though you should check this on your own queries.

Don't fear streaming mode in Polars! 

Streaming lets you work with larger-than-memory data in lazy queries. 

But even for smaller data streaming mode is often as fast or faster than non-streaming queries... https://t.co/vCksP74UP6

‚Ä¢ vertical-viewport-segments

CSS Screen Spanning Media feature consists of specifically designed media queries to help front-end developers optimize the content for Dual Screen or Foldable devices.
